File: South Africa Police Service (SAPS) officers at the Jabulani Mall in the Soweto district of Johannesburg. AFP/Luca Sola JOHANNESBURG - The SA Special Risk Insurance Association has paid out R24-billion in claims relating to last year's unrest. The payout represents 80 percent of all claims lodged with the state-owned insurance company since the July unrest. READ: Sasria warns it can't cover the cost of more unrest The violence claimed more than 300 lives and cost the economy an estimated R50-billion. In a statement, the company says there is R7-billion of outstanding claims to process.